@code_type forth .f

This seemingly small piece of code lets us have subroutines in our
Forth code. A subroutine is a block of code between the words `{` and `}`.
At runtime, the block will push it's execution address onto the stack,
and we can run it with `execute`.

--- bootstrap.f +=
: { immediate
  CLV IFVS
;

: } immediate
  RTS
  dup THEN
  [compile] literal
;
---

Breaking these definitions down, `{` will start an `IF` block that never runs, by
clearing the oVerflow flag and then saying "if overflow is set". This is how we
stop the code from running immediately. Remember that `IFVS` will compile a `bvc`
instruction and push the address of the code onto the stack. That address is the
subroutine address.

Next, we define `}`. We end the subroutine with a return instruction, since we want
go back to where we `execute`d it. `dup` will copy the address that `IFVS` left on the
stack. `THEN` uses that address and changes the `bvc` instruction to branch to the
code after `THEN`.

`[compile] literal` means that when `}` runs, we will execute `literal`, postponing it
instead of running it immediately like normal. It will compile code to push the
subroutine address onto the stack.
Overall, the compiled code for a subroutine will look like this:

@code_type assembly .s
--- subroutine compiled sample
; sample compiled code for: { 1 } execute

  clv
  bvc @skip ; bra
subroutine:
  push #1
  rts
@skip:
  push #subroutine
  jsr EXECUTE
---


